 =20

The basic idea of market manipulation is that you buy a lot of X to make th=
e price of X go up, and then you own a lot of X, which is now worth more th=
an you paid for it. If you start buying Stock X at $50, and you keep buying=
 until you=E2=80=99ve pushed the price up to $100, then you=E2=80=99ve paid=
 an average of, say, $75 per share, but now it=E2=80=99s worth $100 per sha=
re. Good job. But then you try to sell it, to realize that profit, and it s=
tarts going down. If it went up as you bought it, it should go down as you =
sell it. It=E2=80=99ll end up back at $50, maybe lower. You won=E2=80=99t m=
ake any money on the trade.
There is a folk understanding of market manipulation that it is=C2=A0just=
=C2=A0this =E2=80=94=C2=A0just buying stock to make it go up =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0and every so often you see someone accused of this simple version. Bill =
Hwang of Archegos Capital Management is a recent case that we=E2=80=99ve ta=
lked about a lot; he seems to have=C2=A0lost=C2=A0a fortune by buying tons =
of some stocks as they went. up, and then selling them all at once in fire =
sales that crashed their prices. He was arrested for manipulation anyway, a=
nd   I have said: huh?
Instead, for market manipulation to make sense, you need a story that is:
=09I can buy a lot of X and make it go up,=C2=A0and
=09Then I can sell it without making it go down.

In the general case this will not be true. If buying makes X go up, selling=
 will make it go down, and so you can=E2=80=99t make money. There may be sm=
all exceptions; if you have a deep feel for market dynamics, perhaps you ca=
n buy in ways that maximize price impact and sell in ways that minimize it =
and thus make a round-trip profit. (There=E2=80=99s a   fun niche theory th=
at in fact big hedge funds=C2=A0do=C2=A0routinely manipulate stock prices b=
y buying when liquidity is poor in the morning, which pushes up prices, and=
 selling when liquidity is good in the afternoon, which does not push them =
back down.)
But for the most part, the way market manipulation works is that you have s=
ome sort of price-insensitive buyer lined up to sell to before you start bu=
ying to manipulate the price. Often this involves some sort of derivative t=
hat settles by reference to the market price, which you then manipulate. If=
 you have a contract saying that you can sell 100,000 units to your counter=
party at the market price as of 4 p.m., you might consider buying=C2=A0100,=
000 units, as noisily as possible, between 3:58 and 3:59. You=E2=80=99ll pu=
sh up the price a lot with your buying, and then you can just dump it on yo=
ur price-insensitive counterparty at 4 p.m. This is a classic =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0there was a string of   foreign-exchange scandals that looked like this,
  [2]
 and it is  allegedly part of the story of how  oil prices went negative in=
 2020=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0but there are variations. If you have a   one-tou=
ch barrier option, you might want to trade inefficiently to hit the barrier=
.
GMX is a decentralized crypto swap exchange that  advertises =E2=80=9Cno sl=
ippage=E2=80=9D: =E2=80=9CEnter and exit positions with minimal spread and =
zero price impact,=E2=80=9D  it says. Ordinarily the way financial markets =
work is that trades have =E2=80=9Cslippage,=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cprice impa=
ct=E2=80=9D: If you buy a little, the price will go up a little; if you buy=
 a lot, it will go up a lot; if you sell, it will go down.
People find this strangely offensive =E2=80=94=C2=A0a lot of arguments over=
 high-frequency trading in the stock market or liquidity in the bond market=
 come down to =E2=80=9CI want to be able to buy and sell financial assets w=
ithout moving their price=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0and GMX came up with =E2=
=80=A6=C2=A0a =E2=80=A6=C2=A0solution? The solution is that GMX just looks =
at the market price of a token on some other exchange, and then sells you a=
s much as you want of that token (in the form of a perpetual swap) at the m=
arket price: =E2=80=9CThere is  no price impact for trades on GMX, so you c=
an execute large trades exactly at the mark price.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0(This is c=
alled =E2=80=9Coracle=E2=80=9D pricing: GMX=E2=80=99s price comes from look=
ing at the price on other exchanges, rather than from supply and demand on =
GMX itself.)=C2=A0If the Avalanche blockchain=E2=80=99s AVAX token is tradi=
ng at $17 on some exchange, and you want to buy swaps on=C2=A0100,000 AVAX =
tokens on GMX, you=E2=80=99ll pay $17.00 per token. If you went to some oth=
er exchange to actually buy 100,000 AVAX tokens, there would be price impac=
t, and you might end up paying $17.50 or whatever. But on GMX, there is no =
slippage, and you pay $17.00.
You probably know where this is going? I probably don=E2=80=99t need to wri=
te the rest of it? I have that experience a lot, writing about crypto. Ofte=
n it feels like I could=C2=A0just describe the mechanics of how a thing wor=
ks, and then leave it as an exercise for the reader to explain how it was e=
xploited. This one is very easy. Maybe stop reading for a second, figure ou=
t your answer, and then go on to the next paragraph.
So sure yeah  it=E2=80=99s exactly what you thought:

A savvy crypto trader deployed millions of dollars to manipulate the prices=
 of Avalanche=E2=80=99s AVAX tokens on the decentralized exchange (DEX) GMX=
, taking profits of upwards of $500,000 by utilizing a strategy that exploi=
ted a basic loophole. =E2=80=A6
The loophole is that GMX offers trading to users at zero slippage, or the d=
ifference between the expected price of a trade and the price at which the =
trade is executed. But all pricing data on GMX is derived from centralized =
exchanges, such as Binance or FTX, meaning a trader could buy a large numbe=
r of tokens, such as AVAX in this case, on zero slippage, rapidly drive up =
prices on centralized exchanges by placing buy orders on those venues and s=
elling the initial position on GMX at higher prices.
It=E2=80=99s important to note that this strategy will not work on two cent=
ralized exchanges, as a trader placing high bids on one venue would mean pr=
ices automatically move higher on that exchange and other exchanges immedia=
tely raise the price of assets on their own systems =E2=80=93 meaning the s=
trategy is unlikely to net any profits.
In several tweets on Sunday, Genesis Trading head of derivatives Joshua Lim=
 said the trader exploited the GMX loophole some five times, netting over $=
500,000 to $700,000 in total profits.=C2=A0

Here is  Lim=E2=80=99s Twitter thread; he  writes:

This isn't an exploit as much as GMX working as designed! [The trader]=C2=
=A0executed large trades in against [GMX=E2=80=99s decentralized liquidity =
providers]=C2=A0with 0 slippage: at the oracle price without factoring any =
price impact
In the real world, putting on risk requires you to pay liquidity providers =
on the opposite side.

Yes if you can trade a thing in large size without moving its price, and yo=
u can also (on a regular exchange) trade the thing in large size with=C2=A0=
moving its price, then you can print free money, and someone did.

