      Musk vs.=C2=A0Twitter
   =20
 =20

When Elon Musk first started talking about canceling his deal to buy Twitte=
r Inc., what he said was that Twitter had not proved to his satisfaction th=
at fewer than 5% of its =E2=80=9Cmonetizable daily active users=E2=80=9D we=
re spam bots. The deal was =E2=80=9Ctemporarily on hold pending details sup=
porting calculation that spam/fake accounts do indeed represent less than 5=
% of users,=E2=80=9D Musk tweeted, back in May. I   pointed out, back then,=
 that this was   not actually an excuse that could get him out of the deal.=
 The merger agreement didn=E2=80=99t actually say that spam accounts were f=
ewer than 5% of users, for one thing. Even if it had said that, Musk had no=
 evidence that it was wrong. And even if it had said that and was wrong, it=
 wouldn=E2=80=99t give Musk a way out of the deal unless it caused a =E2=80=
=9Cmaterial adverse effect=E2=80=9D on Twitter=E2=80=99s business.
Still, I allowed for the possibility that Musk could win. When he formally =
terminated the deal, in July,   I wrote:
If Musk can prove that in fact Twitter has been running a years-long fraud =
on its shareholders and advertisers =E2=80=94=C2=A0that it has knowingly=C2=
=A0been massively understating the number of bot accounts in order to trick=
 companies into buying Twitter ads and shareholders into buying Twitter sto=
ck =E2=80=94=C2=A0then, sure,=C2=A0maybe=C2=A0that will get him out of the =
deal.=C2=A0
In August, I   put it this way:
Musk=E2=80=99s defense is still that (1) Twitter promised him that fewer th=
an 5% of its monetizable daily active users are bots and (2) Twitter is con=
ducting a massive long-running fraud, it has many fewer users than it claim=
s, and its executives have conspired to deceive investors and advertisers a=
nd cover up its lack of real users.
I was =E2=80=A6=C2=A0=E2=80=9Ckidding=E2=80=9D isn=E2=80=99t the right word=
 here, exactly, but I was being absurd. The point that I was trying to make=
 was that this was not a dispute about how many bots Twitter has, or what i=
nformation Musk was entitled to. If that was the dispute =E2=80=94=C2=A0if =
Musk=E2=80=99s point was =E2=80=9Cactually 6% of Twitter=E2=80=99s mDAUs ar=
e bots=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0then   he would lose immediately. He can=E2=
=80=99t get out of the deal for some sort of good-faith dispute about bot-c=
ounting. His only way out, I wanted to suggest,=C2=A0is if Twitter is a cat=
astrophe, its books are cooked,=C2=A0it was knowingly tricking its sharehol=
ders and Musk for years, and its business is a sham.=C2=A0
I guess my other point was that this was unlikely? Vast long-running conspi=
racies are just rare. People do use Twitter; the idea that it=E2=80=99s a c=
omplete sham seems far-fetched. =E2=80=9CThe pretense that Elon Musk has so=
mehow exposed the secret truth that nobody uses Twitter except himself and =
some spam bots,=E2=80=9D   I called it, back in July.=C2=A0
But what I said half-jokingly,=C2=A0Musk is now saying seriously. Last week=
, Musk filed his amended answer and counterclaims to Twitter=E2=80=99s laws=
uit. Here=E2=80=99s how his  original answer started
  [3]
:
This action arises out of Twitter=E2=80=99s misrepresentations to the Musk =
Parties regarding the condition of the company and the =E2=80=9Ckey metrics=
=E2=80=9D Twitter uses to evaluate the number of users on its platform. Whi=
le the Musk Parties negotiated for representations as to the truth of Twitt=
er=E2=80=99s SEC disclosures, relying on their accuracy, the statements in =
these SEC disclosures were far from true. Instead, they contain numerous, m=
aterial misrepresentations or omissions that distort Twitter=E2=80=99s valu=
e and caused the Musk Parties to agree to acquire the company at an inflate=
d price.
Sounds like a contractual dispute: There=E2=80=99s some disagreement about =
whether Twitter=E2=80=99s statements about bots were true. But here=E2=80=
=99s the new one:=C2=A0
The Musk Parties=E2=80=99 original Counterclaims explained that Twitter has=
 been systematically misrepresenting its =E2=80=9Ckey metric,=E2=80=9D mone=
tizable daily active users (=E2=80=9CmDAU=E2=80=9D), by understating the nu=
mber of false and spam accounts included in mDAU and falsely claiming that =
mDAU was the best way to measure engagement and revenue growth. Stunning ev=
ents over the last week, however, have revealed that the misrepresentations=
 regarding mDAU were only one component of a broader conspiracy among Twitt=
er executives to deceive the public, its investors, and the government abou=
t the dysfunction at the heart of the company. In what can only be describe=
d as one of the most significant whistleblower complaints in recent history=
, a widely respected security expert and former Twitter Chief Security Offi=
cer, Peiter =E2=80=9CMudge=E2=80=9D Zatko, has submitted an 84-page whistle=
blower report to Congress, the FTC, the SEC, and the DOJ, outlining a serie=
s of explosive disclosures regarding misconduct within Twitter. ... Those p=
reviously concealed problems are, according to Zatko, so severe that Zatko=
=E2=80=94who President Biden had asked to lead a national cybersecurity rev=
iew=E2=80=94concluded that they threaten U.S. national security and democra=
cy itself.
The new one is about =E2=80=9Ca broader conspiracy among Twitter executives=
 to deceive the public, its investors, and the government=E2=80=9D in ways =
that could =E2=80=9Cthreaten U.S. national security and democracy itself.=
=E2=80=9D
  [4]
=C2=A0This has gone from being a contractual dispute to being a massive con=
spiracy against democracy itself.
On the one hand: Yes, right, that is what Musk has to do. As I have argued =
from the beginning, he can=E2=80=99t really get out of this deal by quibbli=
ng over bot counting; he has to argue that there=E2=80=99s been a huge inte=
ntional fraud. Now he=E2=80=99s doing that explicitly.
On the other hand: It does raise the difficulty a bit, doesn=E2=80=99t it? =
He has to argue that there=E2=80=99s a huge conspiracy, that Twitter=E2=80=
=99s executives get together and rub their hands together and cackle about =
overthrowing democracy, that Jack Dorsey =E2=80=94=C2=A0Twitter=E2=80=99s c=
o-founder, and Musk=E2=80=99s friend who urged him to buy the company =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0was in on it. The conspiracy stuff can sound a bit far-fetched.
Elsewhere, law professor Robert Anderson  has a paper arguing that it might=
 be hard for a court to actually grant specific performance in this case: t=
hat even if Musk loses all his claims about misrepresentations, fraud, cons=
piracy, etc., a court still shouldn=E2=80=99t force him to close the deal b=
ut should instead make him pay only a $1 billion (or maybe $2 billion) reve=
rse termination fee. As I have  written before,=C2=A0it is=C2=A0weird=C2=A0=
for the merger agreement to say:
=09That because monetary damages can=E2=80=99t possibly compensate Twitter =
for the loss of the deal, the parties agree that there should be specific p=
erformance and Musk can be forced to close even if he doesn=E2=80=99t want =
to; and=09If there are money damages they are capped at $1 billion.

Anderson writes:

This is a cash sale of one of the most well-known and closely followed comp=
anies in the world. Although there are some difficulties assessing damages =
exactly, even in a case like this,=C2=A0they are minimal, and exact computa=
tion isn=E2=80=99t necessary. The shareholders of Twitter simply need to re=
ceive $54.20 in cash or cash equivalents. If damages aren=E2=80=99t adequat=
e in this case, it is difficult to conceive of any M&A case in which they w=
ill be adequate. =E2=80=A6
The primary reason damages would not be adequate in the sense of providing =
full expectation damages in this case is not because they are difficult to =
assess, but because Twitter agreed to cap them. Twitter is entitled to $1 b=
illion in reverse termination fee if the financing falls through, and poten=
tially an additional $1 billion in damages for a =E2=80=9Cknowing and inten=
tional=E2=80=9D breach of the obligation to secure financing. The fact that=
 the parties agreed to cap monetary liability in the form of damages doesn=
=E2=80=99t seem like a reason to impose larger monetary liability through s=
pecific performance. Quite the contrary. In a merger agreement, the reverse=
 termination fee is a highly negotiated provision the parties use to alloca=
te risk; in contrast, the specific performance section is boilerplate text =
copied and pasted into the =E2=80=9CGeneral Provisions=E2=80=9D at the end =
of the agreement. The boilerplate section at the end is an unlikely candida=
te for the parties to add $20 billion in settlement value to the otherwise =
carefully capped liability provisions.

As Anderson says, this is a standard feature of private-equity merger agree=
ments: Damages tend to be capped at some relatively small number, but the a=
greements also allow specific performance. Here, specific performance is wo=
rth something like $20 billion to Twitter, while the damages are capped at =
$1 billion. You can sort of understand the rationale: Forcing Musk to buy T=
witter might be fairer to him than forcing him to pay $20 billion of damage=
s and=C2=A0not get Twitter;=C2=A0if he buys the company at least he has a s=
hot of making his money back, while if he terminates and gets sued for dama=
ges and loses he just has to write a huge check for nothing. Still it is a =
weird binary, where Twitter gets either everything it wants or almost nothi=
ng.

