9474188" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" s=
tyle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wid=
th: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgrou=
nd-color: #ccc;"> it=E2=80=99s exactly what you thought</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A savvy crypto trader deployed millions of dol=
lars to manipulate the prices of Avalanche=E2=80=99s AVAX tokens on the dec=
entralized exchange (DEX) GMX, taking profits of upwards of $500,000 by uti=
lizing a strategy that exploited a basic loophole. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The loophole is that GMX offers trading to use=
rs at zero slippage, or the difference between the expected price of a trad=
e and the price at which the trade is executed. But all pricing data on GMX=
 is derived from centralized exchanges, such as Binance or FTX, meaning a t=
rader could buy a large number of tokens, such as AVAX in this case, on zer=
o slippage, rapidly drive up prices on centralized exchanges by placing buy=
 orders on those venues and selling the initial position on GMX at higher p=
rices.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It=E2=80=99s important to note that this strat=
egy will not work on two centralized exchanges, as a trader placing high bi=
ds on one venue would mean prices automatically move higher on that exchang=
e and other exchanges immediately raise the price of assets on their own sy=
stems =E2=80=93 meaning the strategy is unlikely to net any profits.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In several tweets on Sunday, Genesis Trading h=
ead of derivatives Joshua Lim said the trader exploited the GMX loophole so=
me five times, netting over $500,000 to $700,000 in total profits.=C2=A0</p=
>
</blockquote>
